TEXT.1: ***Important Notes*** on Accuracy of VperpM_MF (meridional),VperpZ_MF (zonal), and VparaMF (parallel) components.

TEXT.2: Geophysical flow components VperpM_MF, VperpZ_MF, and VparaMF are converted from flow velocities, Vx, Vy, and Vz

TEXT.3: measured in the S/C coordinate system. Vx points along the S/C trajectory vector, Vz is in the nadir direction,

TEXT.4: and Vy points to the right of the S/C trajectory vector (in the anti-angular momentum direction).

TEXT.5: 1) Vx, Vy, and Vz are measured flow velocities at S/C coordinate in the Earth-centered Inertia Coordinate System (non-rotating) (ECI coordinate).

TEXT.6: 2) VperZ_MF, VperM_MF, and VparaMF are geophysical flows in the Earth-centered Fixed Coordinated System (rotate with the Earth) (ECF coordinate).

TEXT.7: 3) Uncertainty of +-(37.8-75.45) m/s in Vx based on 0.5% - 1% error in fitting could be introduced to all geophysical flow components.

TEXT.8: 4) VperpM_MF at low latitude is almost identical to (-Vz). No Vx is included so that it is very reliable.

TEXT.9: 5) Uncertainties from Vx could exist in VperpZ_MF and VparaMF.

TEXT.10: 6) VperpZ_MF and VparaMF can be used to study the relative changes in flow velocity due to  geophysical effects.

TEXT.11: But can not be used to study the long-term variations because the result could be biased by the uncertainty in Vx.
